equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic core context drives V/I competition; V wins via late attention
equation_narrative.story: Position 23 in ubiquitin sits in a hydrophobic core environment with 9 structural contacts. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation consistent with buried hydrophobic residues, reading predominantly nonpolar contacts and minimal co-evolutionary signal. The logit lens shows unstable early leadership among hydrophobic candidates (A, L, T) as the representation character stabilizes. At layer 27, the decision phase begins: V emerges as the leading candidate, briefly yields to I at L28-30 (peaking at 72% for I at L30), but V reclaims dominance in the final layers through strong attention-driven features (F33:6423, 102.16 proj) that favor the slightly smaller branched hydrophobic. The model correctly identifies the hydrophobic character but selects V over the true I.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 focus on reading the hydrophobic core environment. Nine structural contacts provide strong nonpolar signal, with attention heads at L12 (head 1, -1.839 proj) and L10 (head 0, -1.221 proj) reading local and structural context heavily. Only 2 co-evolving positions contribute, indicating this is primarily a structure-driven site. Early SAE features (F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 all ~45 proj) encode positional and local sequence context. The logit lens shows frequent lead changes between hydrophobic candidates (A peaks at 20% at L0, L dominates L3-L21 reaching 26% at L17, T rises to 38% at L24), reflecting the model's evolving representation of a buried hydrophobic position rather than prediction attempts. By L23, the representation stabilizes with T at 25%, L at 17%, and V/I emerging at 11%/7%.
perception_phase.context_character: Buried hydrophobic core environment with 9 structural contacts, minimal co-evolutionary constraint (2 positions), and strong local sequence signal from surrounding nonpolar residues (EPSDT[?]ENVKA). The representation is consistently hydrophobic-leaning throughout perception.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 9 residues within contact distance, predominantly hydrophobic character
Co-evolutionary signal: weak (2 positions only), suggesting structure-dominated constraint
L9 attention features: F9:5728 (64.03 proj), F9:1281 (58.8 proj) encode structural context
L18 features: F18:6256 (13.58 proj), F18:5712 (13.47 proj) refine hydrophobic character
MLP L10-L23: steady accumulation of hydrophobic signal (N10:3108 votes for I at 0.234, N13:1157 votes for I at 0.38)

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L27 when V first takes the lead (40.6%), but I immediately challenges, peaking at 72% at L30 through strong MLP support (N29:644 projects 1.014 toward I, N30:3697 projects 0.531). However, the final layers L32-33 see a dramatic reversal: attention features strongly favor V (F33:6423 at 102.16 proj, F33:4166 at 98.31 proj), while MLP neurons in L32 actively suppress I (N32:3735 erases -1.03, N32:4472 erases -0.982). V surges from 54% to 77% in the final layer through attention-driven writes (L32 head 12 projects 1.875, L32 head 18 projects 1.658).
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, the representation shifts from encoding context to selecting candidates. T briefly spikes to 39% at L24 (driven by F24:3692 at 20.84 proj) as the first amino-acid-specific prediction channel, but this polar candidate is quickly suppressed. By L25, hydrophobic-specific features dominate (N25:4019 projects 0.76 toward I), marking the transition to genuine prediction.

candidates.narrative: V emerges at L27 (40.6%) and dominates the final decision through exceptionally strong late-layer attention features. At L30, V briefly trails I (37.8% vs 56.4%), but L32-33 attention heads write decisively for V: F33:6423 (102.16 proj), F33:4166 (98.31 proj), and F33:7165 (94.14 proj) are all attention-sourced V-specific channels. The final surge from 54% to 77% at L33 is driven by structural attention (L32 head 12 projects 1.875, L32 head 18 projects 1.658) that favors the slightly smaller branched hydrophobic over I.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L27, challenged L28-30, dominant L32-33
key_evidence: L32 head 12 (1.875 proj) — structural writer favoring V
N23:3627 (1.341 proj toward I, 1.559 toward V) — early V preference

candidates.narrative: I is the true amino acid but finishes second at 20.79%. I shows strong mid-decision support, rising from 7% at L23 to peak at 72% at L30 through powerful MLP neurons (N29:644 projects 1.014, N31:2104 projects 1.006). However, I loses catastrophically in the final layers: L32-33 MLP neurons actively suppress I (N32:3735 erases -1.03, N32:4472 erases -0.982), while attention features overwhelmingly favor V. The model correctly reads the hydrophobic core context but selects the wrong branched aliphatic.
candidates.key_layers: Rises L25-30 (peaks 72% at L30), collapses L31-33
key_evidence: N29:644 (1.014 proj) — strongest I-specific MLP neuron
N32:3735 (-1.03 proj) — critical I suppression at L32
F30:7696 (MLP, 20.92 proj) — I-supporting feature before collapse

candidates.narrative: T leads the logit lens from L10-L26, peaking at 39% at L24. This reflects the representation's character during perception: T is polar but small, and the logit lens projects toward it as the model encodes a compact position with some polar-compatible features. T is NOT a genuine candidate—it's an artifact of the representation's intermediate state. At L24, F24:3692 (20.84 proj) briefly activates as a T-specific channel, but this is immediately suppressed as hydrophobic-specific features dominate. T collapses to 2% by L29.
candidates.key_layers: Logit-lens leader L10-L26, peaks L24, suppressed L25+
key_evidence: F24:3692 (attn, 20.84 proj) — transient T-specific feature at decision boundary
Logit lens: 25% at L23, 39% at L24, 2% at L29
N13:2906 (-0.239 proj) — T eraser in perception phase

candidates.narrative: L dominates the logit lens through mid-perception (L3-L21), peaking at 26% at L17. This reflects the representation's strong hydrophobic character as the model reads nonpolar structural contacts. L's prominence is a logit-lens artifact: the representation is consistent with large hydrophobic residues, and L projects well through the unembedding. However, L never activates as a genuine candidate in the decision phase—it collapses to 1% by L29 as more specific branched-hydrophobic features (V/I) take over.

key_evidence: Logit lens: 26% at L17, 17% at L23, 1% at L29

candidates.narrative: A leads the logit lens at embedding (20% at L0) and remains visible through L12 (15% at L12). This early prominence reflects the representation's initial encoding of a small, hydrophobic-compatible position before structural contacts are fully integrated. A is purely a logit-lens artifact of the early representation state—it never receives decision-phase support and fades to 0.5% by L33.

No decision-phase features or MLP support

turning_points.description: The representation stabilizes around large hydrophobic character. MLP neurons accumulate hydrophobic signal (L10 total_answer_proj 1.52, L17 total_answer_proj 1.82), with N10:3108, N13:1157, and N17:203 all writing toward I. The logit lens shows L peaking at 26% at L17, reflecting the representation's compatibility with large nonpolar residues. Attention heads read structural contacts heavily (L12 head 1 erases -1.839 with 93% structural attention), integrating the buried core environment.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs. At L23, the representation is still context-encoding (T at 25%, L at 17%). L24 sees the first amino-acid-specific prediction channel activate (F24:3692 for T at 20.84 proj), but this polar candidate is immediately rejected. By L25, hydrophobic-specific MLP neurons dominate (N25:4019 projects 0.76 toward I, N25:45 projects 0.487), marking the shift to genuine prediction. The model commits to branched hydrophobics (V+I combined rise from 18% to 40%).

The V/I competition resolves through attention dominance. I peaks at 72% at L30 via MLP support (N29:644 at 1.014 proj, N30:3697 at 0.531 proj). However, L32-33 attention features overwhelmingly favor V: F33:6423 (102.16 proj), F33:4166 (98.31 proj), and structural attention heads (L32 head 12 at 1.875 proj, L30 head 6 at 2.088 proj) write decisively for V. Simultaneously, L32 MLP neurons suppress I (N32:3735 at -1.03, N32:4472 at -0.982). V surges from 41% to 77% in L27-33.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention L10-L18
deep_dives.caption: These attention heads read the 9 structural contacts to build the hydrophobic core representation. L12 head 1 shows 93% structural attention with -1.839 projection (erasing non-hydrophobic signal), while L10 head 0 shows 87% structural attention with -1.221 projection. This is the model's primary mechanism for encoding burial and local chemistry during perception.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L9-L18
deep_dives.caption: Early SAE features encode the hydrophobic structural context. F9:5728 (64.03 proj), F9:1281 (58.8 proj), and F9:2619 (58.02 proj) are all attention-sourced features that integrate structural contacts. By L18, features like F18:6256 (13.58 proj) and F18:5712 (13.47 proj) refine the representation toward compact hydrophobics.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L23-L25
deep_dives.caption: The perception-to-decision transition. L23 shows N23:3627 strongly favoring V (1.559 proj) and I (1.341 proj), the first clear branched-hydrophobic preference. L24 has net negative answer projection (-2.57) as polar candidates are rejected. L25 commits to I/V with N25:4019 (0.76 proj toward I) and N25:45 (0.487 proj toward I).

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L29-L31 (I peak)
deep_dives.caption: I's peak support comes from these layers. N29:644 projects 1.014 toward I (strongest single neuron), N30:3697 projects 0.531, and N31:2104 projects 1.006. These neurons recognize the specific branched-hydrophobic context that favors I. However, this MLP support is insufficient against the attention-driven V preference in final layers.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L30-L33
deep_dives.caption: Decision-phase prediction channels. L30 shows F30:9387 (attn, 22.45 proj) and several MLP features (F30:7696 at 20.92, F30:3785 at 20.9) supporting I. But L33 attention features overwhelmingly favor V: F33:6423 (102.16 proj), F33:4166 (98.31 proj), F33:7165 (94.14 proj). These high-projection attention features are V-specific prediction channels that override MLP I-support.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L32 (I suppression)
deep_dives.caption: L32 MLP neurons actively suppress I in the final decision. N32:3735 erases -1.03 from I (voting for A/M/S instead), N32:4472 erases -0.982 (voting for N/D/A), and N32:3026 erases -0.699 (voting for A/G/C). Total answer projection is -7.04, the most negative of any layer. This suppression, combined with attention's V-preference, causes I's collapse from 72% to 21%.

deep_dives.label: Attention heads L30-L32 (V writers)
deep_dives.caption: The decisive structural attention writes for V. L30 head 6 projects 2.088 with 18% structural attention, L32 head 12 projects 1.875 with 20% structural attention, and L32 head 18 projects 1.658 with 36% structural attention. These heads read the compact hydrophobic environment and favor V's slightly smaller branched structure over I.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly identifies position 23 as a buried hydrophobic core site through 9 structural contacts and assembles a representation strongly consistent with branched aliphatic residues. The V/I competition is decided by late-layer attention features that favor V's slightly smaller size: F33:6423 (102.16 proj), F33:4166 (98.31 proj), and structural attention heads (L32 head 12 at 1.875 proj) override strong MLP support for I (N29:644 at 1.014 proj). The model's error suggests it weights subtle size constraints from the structural environment more heavily than the specific packing geometry that would distinguish I from V.
